thread.title: ASU sharpens focus amid wide-open Pac-12 South

title: ASU sharpens focus amid wide-open Pac-12 South
text:
The question from the audience had to do with Arizona State looking ahead, past Colorado and onto the Sun Devils' Oct. 17 showdown at Utah, the No. 5 team in the country.
"It shouldn't be hard because of where we've been the first four games. We've played really one complete football game,'' coach Todd Graham answered during his weekly radio show. "… This is pretty competitive. It's not easy, but anything worth having is tough. Our guys are not looking past the next rep. We have to figure out a way to be 1-0, and we can worry about Utah after that."
Radio host Tim Healey interjected: "By the way, a quick update for you. How about this? In the third quarter, the Washington Huskies have just taken a 10-6 lead on USC in a game being played at the Coliseum."
Graham didn't hesitate.
"Point made,'' he said.
AZCENTRAL
ASU vs. Colorado scouting report, prediction
***
Ten days ago, ASU fans and media criticized coaching calls and quarterback decisions. Thursday night – after Washington defeated USC in Los Angeles – they discussed how the Sun Devils (3-2, 1-1 in the Pac-12) suddenly control their destiny in the Pac-12 South.
First of all, six weeks remain in the regular season. Talking about a college football team controlling its destiny at this point is like discussing a major-league baseball team's magic number at the All-Star break. It's much too early. At the same time, this also might just be the theme of this year's Pac-12 South.
Craziness.
Utah has emerged as the division leader, but after that, a pecking order has yet to take form. Just when you start to feel good about one team, they lose. Just when you're about to dismiss another, they win.
AZCENTRAL
Rich Rodriguez 28th, Todd Graham 33rd on list of highest-paid college football head coaches
"I think it's a lot of what we thought," said Pac-12 Networks analyst Yogi Roth, who will work Saturday's ASU-Colorado contest. "We knew it was going to be hectic."
He broke down each team:
ASU: "Early on, they were disappointing, but you could attribute that to the injuries they had and they didn't really get to practice well, let alone practice fast. But now after last week's win at UCLA, they probably look as good as any team in the South, top to bottom."
USC: "In my opinion, USC had always gotten too much hype. Even though (Thursday) night's loss was an embarrassing one, they have 13 freshmen playing. I don't care who you are or how good the recruits are, that to me is a reality that should not go unnoticed. … They're still so young."
UCLA: "No one would have predicted the deepest team in the Pac-12 – and one of the deepest in the country – would have five defensive starters not playing a week ago against Arizona State."
AZCENTRAL
ASU XTRA app: Get latest news, analysis, scores, photos
Arizona: "You look at what they did a year ago -- what'd they have (six) games they won by a touchdown or less? You kind of knew it could go either way, then they lose their best player (in linebacker Scooby Wright )."
Utah: "They've just been Steady Eddie. You have to give credit to (quarterback) Travis Wilson, and to (coach) Kyle Whittingham for what he's always done on defense."
Colorado: "Of course, they're exactly who we thought. They're going to be on the verge of knocking somebody off, and they'll probably do it this year."
Entering Saturday, that's ASU's concern.
AZCENTRAL
ASU notes: Backup QB Manny Wilkins preparing for his time
***
Truth: Colorado (3-2, 0-1) is easy to overlook. The Buffaloes have lost 10 consecutive conference games. They have not won a conference road game since 2012. In four seasons under Graham, ASU has won each meeting by an average of nearly 30 points.
At the same time, the Sun Devils are just two weeks removed from committing four turnovers in a 42-14 loss to USC. In five weeks, they have looked the part of conference contender exactly once, in last week's UCLA win . The defense has played at a high level, but the offense has struggled to establish rhythm and finish drives.
As a result, ASU's message has not changed.
AZCENTRAL
Boivin: ASU, UA additions highlight Pac-12's 100 years
"Just like I said last week,'' offensive coordinator Mike Norvell said. "My concern was not UCLA. My concern the week before was not USC. My No. 1 concern is us. As long as we keep focusing on ourselves and keep getting better each and every day, I think this offense will continue to grow."
Junior receiver Tim White thinks the Sun Devils are close.
"It's just a matter of being on point,'' he said. "Last week, we had a great week of practice and this week we had a great week of practice. It's just a matter of continuing it."
Contact Doug Haller at 602-444-4949 or at Doug.Haller@arizonarepublic.com. Follow him at Twitter.com/DougHalle r.
Arizona State hosts Colorado at 7 p.m. Saturday. Doug Haller offers his scouting report and prediction. Michael Chow/azcentral sports Fullscreen ASU FIRST AND FOREMOST | The Sun Devils (3-2, 1-1 in the Pac-12) are coming off last week's 38-23 upset win over then-No. 7 UCLA. They never have lost to Colorado in six tries. In three meetings under coach Todd Graham, ASU has won by an average of 29.6 points. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen ASU KEY PLAYER | Tim White. The junior receiver nearly returned a kick-off for a touchdown in last week's win. Don't be surprised if he breaks another long run this week. In the passing game, White has 13 catches for 134 yards and three touchdowns. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen ASU KEY STAT | 8 - Through five games, ASU has given up only eight rushing plays of 20-plus yards, and three have come off quarterback scrambles. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen COLORADO FIRST AND FOREMOST | The Buffaloes (3-2, 0-1) are coming off last week's 41-24 home loss to Oregon, a game that was closer than the final score indicates. Even so, they have lost 10 conference games in a row. Ron Chenoy-USA TODAY Sports Fullscreen COLORADO KEY PLAYER | Nelson Spruce. The senior receiver -- a 2014 second-team All-Pac-12 selection -- has 31 catches for 363 yards and a touchdown -- and has yet to have a breakout game. Last season he had five 100-yard receiving games. Ron Chenoy-USA TODAY Sports Fullscreen COLORADO KEY STAT | 12 - Colorado has lost 12 consecutive conference road games, a streak that dates to 2012. Byron Hetzler-USA TODAY Sports Fullscreen ASU ON OFFENSE | The Sun Devils are coming off their best offensive performance, but they still have room to grow. They average 27.6 points per game (11th in the Pac-12) and 5.5 yards per play (tied for 10th). Behind RBs Demario Richard (101.6 rushing yards per game) and Kalen Ballage (44.5), ASU will try to establish the run. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen QB Mike Bercovici added to this effort against UCLA, rushing for three first downs, including a 34-yard TD. Overall, Bercovici – the Pac-12 Offensive Player of the Week -- averages 268.8 passing yards per game (fourth in the Pac-12), but completes just 59.7 percent of his attempts (11th). Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen WR D.J. Foster has 26 catches (fifth in the Pac-12) for 246 yards and 2 TDs. The Sun Devils rank 100th nationally in red-zone efficiency, producing just 13 TDs in 23 drives.Colorado allows 21.4 points (fifth in the Pac-12) and 5.2 yards per play (tied for sixth.) Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen The Buffaloes have forced 10 turnovers. Their 8 INTs rank second in the Pac-12 and 14th nationally. Colorado likely will be without top LBs Kenneth Olugbode and Addison Gillam because of injuries. | Advantage: ASU. Ron Chenoy-USA TODAY Sports Fullscreen ASU ON DEFENSE | The Sun Devils give up 26.8 points per game (10th in the Pac-12) and 5.0 yards per play (fourth in the Pac-12). Remove Cal Poly and New Mexico – triple-option teams that liked to run on nearly every down – and ASU has allowed 105.3 rushing yards against Texas A&M, USC and UCLA. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen LB Salamo Fiso – who leads the country in solo tackles – leads a unit that ranks sixth nationally with 44 TFLs. Colorado averages 33.4 points (eight in the Pac-12) and 5.4 yards per play (11th). The Buffaloes – which rush on 59 percent of their total plays -- have topped 200 rushing yards in three of their five games Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen Overall, they average 233 rushing yards per game, which rank third in the Pac-12. RB Michael Adkins (70.7 rushing yards per game) is questionable with a hamstring issue. Phillip Lindsay and Christian Powell both average over 5 yards per carry. Ron Chenoy-USA TODAY Sports Fullscreen QB Sefo Liufau has played through shoulder issues, completing 59.2 percent of his attempts with 5 TDs and 2 INTs. WR Nelson Spruce is his top target and among the Pac-12's best at his position. | Advantage: ASU Ron Chenoy-USA TODAY Sports Fullscreen SPECIAL TEAMS | ASU shined last week. Matt Haack – the Pac-12's Special Teams Player of the Week – had a game-changing punt in the fourth quarter. Overall, he averages 43.6 yards per punt, which ranks third in the Pac-12 and 32nd nationally. Twelve of his 30 punts have been downed inside the 20. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen K Zane Gonzalez has a 70.4 touchback percentage, which ranks ninth nationally, but has made just 5 of 9 FGs, none longer than 31 yards. Tim White averages 28.9 yards on kick-off returns, which ranks 18th nationally. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen Colorado's Diego Gonzalez has made 9 of 12 FGs with a long of 52 yards. Alex Kinney has a 38.3-yard punting average, which ranks 11th in the Pac-12. Behind returners Donovan Lee and Phillip Lindsay, Colorado ranks 15th nationally in kick-off returns (27.3 yards). | Advantage: ASU Ron Chenoy-USA TODAY Sports Fullscreen BOTTOM LINE | With a trip to Utah waiting next week, ASU needs to build off last week's UCLA win. The offense still has a lot to clean up, particularly in the red zone. Sticking with Richard and Ballage in the running game will help. Also, count on a big special teams play for the second week in a row. Rob Schumacher/azcentral sports Fullscreen PREDICTION | ASU 37, Colorado 24.
